english:
  title: A Letter Regarding Master Wu's Eastern Pavilion and His Discourse on Tidal Waters
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: "On this day, I, Lee, a mere official of modest station, humbly bow twice and submit this letter to the esteemed Master of the Eastern Pavilion.\n\nI am but a dull and unpolished man who, even before reaching manhood, had already turned away from my peers to seek companionship with learned elders like yourself. Yet never have I encountered a sage of such breadth and truth as you. Day after day in your presence, I hear what I have never heard before. You are more than thirty years my senior—it would have been fitting had you treated me as a son or younger brother—and yet you have honored me with friendship that transcends the boundaries of age. How dare I presume to accept such grace?\n\nThe other day you visited my humble dwelling and inquired after my recent compositions. As you were perusing them, you spoke to me at ease, saying: \"I have long possessed a Discourse on Tidal Waters, which I have never shown to anyone. Since you are a lover of learning, should you visit me again, I shall show it to you.\" Upon hearing this, I thought to myself: \"Though the present age does not lack elderly scholars and learned men skilled in letters and versed in antiquity, this master deems me worthy of instruction and wishes to share the treasures locked away in his chest. A person such as I should feel endless honor and gratitude.\" Several days later, I came to pay my respects and made request of this promise, only to have you suddenly reverse your words, saying: \"My discourse is not worth viewing. Since you too are a writer, should you first compose your own treatise or essay expounding the origins of the tides, then I shall show you mine.\" Yet in the end, you would not permit me to see it. Since I had not previously known of this discourse's existence, and since you yourself first mentioned it, I did not hesitate to travel the distance to your gate—only to be denied. How deeply I lament this!\n\nAlas, my study has been brief and my understanding shallow, for I am but a young scholar. How could I possibly comprehend the principles by which the tides advance and retreat, wax and wane? And if I could comprehend them, why would I then desperately seek your discourse? \n\nThe principles governing birds and beasts, plants and trees in their eternal birth and transformation; the numbers of yin and yang, odd and even; the seasonal shifts of heat and cold—these matters seem shrouded in obscurity, beyond mortal knowing. Yet the classics and histories discourse upon them in great detail, and so any scholar, however imperfect in understanding, has grasped at least some glimmer of their truth. I alone remain mired in ignorance, and only because my years are few and my faculties weak, my reading undiligent. How much more so with the origins of the tides—a subject upon which even the ancients rarely spoke! How could I, insignificant as I am, presume to untangle it with my meager wit, only to invite the laughter and ridicule of the learned men of our time?\n\nYet I believe I understand your true intention. You have surely reckoned that I shall never produce a treatise on the tides, and so you have set before me an impossible standard, barring the very gate through which I might enter, wishing to keep your discourse hidden. Perhaps you deemed me a deluded fool lacking all discernment, unworthy to behold your work? If so, then your promise to show it to me was but deception, mere mockery. Is this the way of a faithful gentleman who holds sacred the principle of never deceiving others? Or is it that I was deemed worthy of instruction yesterday, yet today you judge me mad and foolish? Or perhaps you believe the world has no one capable of understanding, and so you guard your manuscript for posterity, waiting for some future sage to appreciate what your contemporaries cannot? If so, then you deny those of us who live in your own time the sweetness of your wisdom, reserving this rare and exquisite taste for some distant heir who will savor what we could never know. This seems neither just nor fitting, and I cannot believe such is your intention.\n\nYet I do not understand your true purpose. If you mean to keep this discourse sealed forever, then it lies beyond what I deserve, and I shall harbor no further hope. I ask only one thing: that you reveal to me your intent. I humbly beseech you to listen.\n\nYour thesis must surely rest upon solid foundation. Upon what books do you draw? What ancient authorities do you cite? If you base it upon the *Water Classic*, then that work already contains such discussion—why need another treatise from you? If you cite Lu Zhao, then his famous rhapsody already treats the matter thoroughly, and I cannot imagine your discourse would revisit what he has perfected.\n\nI have heard that even Buddhist scholars discourse upon the tides, yet they do so merely to support their teachings, not to conduct any special inquiry into the nature of sea waters. But to use Buddhist thought as a standard would reveal a weakness in Confucianism itself. Confucianism preceded Buddhism and claims to comprehend heaven and earth—must Confucian scholars now rely upon Buddhist doctrine to speak of such things? This cannot serve as valid foundation.\n\nAs for the other accounts of old—that terrestrial currents respond to the sea, that living creatures breathe in rhythm with cosmic forces, that the deities Yang Hou and Ling Xu stir the waters in their wrath—these are hardly worthy of consideration.\n\nGiven your vast knowledge and broad learning, surely you possess some novel insight to share with the scholarly world, something to astound and awaken all who hear it. Why then do you seal your chambers so firmly and refuse so adamantly?\n\nI have myself attempted to reconcile the *Water Classic* with Lu Zhao's rhapsody. The *Classic* speaks of how loaches emerge and retreat according to season, and thus the tides have their fixed times—yet this seems far too simple, and I myself cannot fully credit it. Only Lu Xia-zhou has boldly cut through the doubt, declaring that the tides advance and retreat according to the sun, and that their waxing and waning are one with the moon's transformations. He posed fourteen questions and answered each, penetrating to the finest subtlety of principle and exhausting the nature of all things. His method harmonizes perfectly with the systems of the *Book of Changes* and the celestial sphere. This I have held as certain truth, and I believe that none who come after could surpass it.\n\nWhen I heard that you had composed a discourse on this subject, my eagerness to see it burned as fiercely as a thirsty man's thirst for drink, as an itching man's need to scratch. Not for a moment have I ceased longing for it.\n\nI earnestly beseech you not to keep your precious wisdom hidden, but to grant me one word that illuminates your reasoning and sources. Allow this dull student to have the scales fall from his eyes, that I might see the brilliant patterns of your prose as clearly as woven silk, and hear the harmonies of your wisdom as distinctly as ancient music. This would truly be the way of a great gentleman in nurturing those who come after.\n\nI remain your humble servant, bowing twice."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Lu Zhao (盧肇), also known as Lu Xia-zhou, was a Tang Dynasty poet and scholar famous for his rhapsody on the tides.
  - key: ''
    value: The *Water Classic* (水經) is a classical Chinese geographical and hydrological text.
  - key: ''
    value: The fourteen questions refer to Lu Zhao's systematic investigation into the relationship between lunar phases and tidal movements.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Discourse on Tidal Waters' mentioned throughout was apparently a scholarly work that the addressee had promised but refused to share.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Woven silk patterns'' (黼黻) and ''ancient music'' (韶濩) are metaphorical expressions for refined knowledge and wisdom in classical Chinese literature.'
